'''Peter Plaoul''' (1353–1415; {{lang-la|Petrus Plaoul}}, {{lang-fr|Pierre Plaoul}}) was a late medieval [[Scholastic philosophy|Scholastic philosopher]] and [[theologian]]. Born in [[Liège|Liege]], he was educated at the [[University of Paris]] and remained an active member of the University until he was made [[Bishop of Senlis]] in 1409.

While the content of his thought remains relatively unknown, Plaoul is often noted for his role in ending the [[Western Schism|Great Schism]]. He was present at the three French clergy councils in the 1390s called by [[Charles VI, Holy Roman Emperor|King Charles the VI]]. There he advocated for the withdrawal of obedience from the [[Avignon Papacy|Avignon Pope]]. He was also a speaker at the [[Council of Pisa]], where the members attempted to end the schism by electing a third pope. Peter became sick and died before he could take part in the [[Council of Constance]], which finally brought an end to the schism.

