{{Infobox philosopher |region = [[Western philosophy]] |era = [[Contemporary philosophy|21st century Philosophy]] |color = |image = |name = '''Stephen H. Daniel''' |birth_date = {{b-da|June 9, 1950}} |birth_place = [[Salisbury, North Carolina]] |death_date = |death_place = |school_tradition = [[Continental philosophy|Continental]] |main_interests = philosophy of [[George Berkeley]] |notable_ideas = | spouse = | education = | alma_mater = [[Saint Louis University]] |influences = [[George Berkeley]], [[Leibniz]], [[Jonathan Edwards (theologian)|Jonathan Edwards]] |influenced = |awards = Presidential Professor for Teaching Excellence }}
'''Stephen H. Daniel''' (born June 9, 1950 in [[Salisbury, North Carolina]]) is an American philosopher and professor of [[philosophy]] at [[Texas A&M University]]. He is known for his expertise on [[George Berkeley]]. Daniel is the senior editor of ''[[Berkeley Studies]]'' and was the president of [[International Berkeley Society]] between 2006 and 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Daniel Stepping Down after 10 Years; Kendrick to Assume Presidency|url=http://internationalberkeleysociety.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/briefs-july-15.pdf|website=[[International Berkeley Society]]|accessdate=9 June 2017}}</ref>
==Books== * ''Contemporary Continental Thought'', NJ: Prentice-Hall, 2005 * ''The Philosophy of Jonathan Edwards: A Study in Divine Semiotics''. Bloomington: Indiana University Press, 1994 * ''Myth and Modern Philosophy''. Philadelphia: Temple University Press, 1990 * ''John Toland: His Methods, Manners, and Mind''. Montreal: McGill-Queen’s University Press, 1984
